    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>The Nobel Prize Museum is located at Stortorget 2 in Gamla Stan, Stockholm, occupying the former Stock Exchange building (Börshuset) on the main square of the medieval old town. The museum opened in 2001 and is dedicated to the Nobel Prize, its laureates, and the ideas and discoveries that have been recognised since the first awards in 1901. The museum is operated by Nobel Prize Outreach, a subsidiary of the Nobel Foundation. The permanent exhibition — titled "These things changed the world" — presents artefacts from laureates alongside an account of how their discoveries, insights, and peace efforts have influenced daily life. Changing temporary exhibitions cover individual laureates or themes related to current prize categories.</p>
    <p>A guided tour is included in every admission ticket and runs daily. English-language tours take place at 11:15, 13:15, and 15:15; an additional tour runs at 19:00 on Fridays. Swedish-language tours run at 14:15. There is a limited number of places per tour — visitors register at the entrance desk on arrival. Pre-booking is not available. An audio guide covering the exhibitions is available in eight languages (Swedish, English, Spanish, German, Italian, French, Japanese, and Hungarian) as well as a children's version in English and Swedish, accessible via visitors' own smartphones at audio.nobelprizemuseum.se. Bistro Nobel, the museum café, is located on site.</p>
    <p>Tickets are sold at the entrance desk only and are not available for purchase through the museum's website. Card payment is the only accepted method (VISA, Mastercard, American Express, Maestro) — no cash is accepted. Children and youth aged 0–18 are admitted free of charge at all times. The museum is closed on Mondays except during Swedish school holidays. Friday evenings until 21:00 regularly feature events, concerts, talks, and other programming. The museum is accessible for visitors with reduced mobility, with a cloakroom offering limited lockers. Conversion rate used: 1 SEK ≈ €0.087 (March 2026). Last updated: March 2026 · Verified</p>
