  <div class="sec">
    <div class="sec-t">FAQ</div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">How much does the Nobel Prize Museum cost in 2026?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Adult SEK 160 (approx. €14.00). Student and senior citizen SEK 120 (approx. €10.50). Free for children and youth aged 0–18 and for Nobel Prize Museum members. A guided tour is included in the admission ticket. Tickets are sold at the entrance desk only — not available online. Card payment only (VISA, Mastercard, American Express, Maestro). No cash accepted.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">What are Nobel Prize Museum opening hours?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Tuesday–Thursday 11:00–17:00. Friday 11:00–21:00. Saturday–Sunday 11:00–17:00. Closed Mondays, except during Swedish school holidays. Closed 19 June (Midsummer Eve), 24–25 December, and 31 December. Last entry is 15 minutes before closing. Check nobelprizemuseum.se for current irregular hours.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Is a guided tour included at the Nobel Prize Museum?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Yes. A guided tour is included in the admission fee at no extra cost. Tours run daily. English tours at 11:15, 13:15, and 15:15 daily; Friday also at 19:00. Swedish tours at 14:15. Register at the entrance on arrival — pre-booking is not available. Limited slots per tour.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Where is the Nobel Prize Museum in Stockholm?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Stortorget 2, Gamla Stan — in the former Stock Exchange building on the main square of the medieval old town. The nearest metro station is Gamla Stan (T-bana lines 13 and 14), a 2-minute walk. Bus lines 2, 3, and 53 stop at Riddarhustorget. Bus lines 2, 57, and 76 stop at Slottsbacken.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Can I buy Nobel Prize Museum tickets online?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">No. Tickets are sold at the entrance desk only and are not available on nobelprizemuseum.se. Any third-party site selling advance tickets is a reseller charging a markup on a walk-up ticket. There is no benefit to buying through a reseller — no timed entry slots exist and no queue forms requiring advance booking. Buy at the door and save the markup.</div>
    </div>
